voice_to_text: Seeing a beautiful woman fall from a truck into the water, Jason dove in without hesitation to rescue her. But once he pulled her out, he realized she was nothing more than a doll. He didn't know whether to laugh or cry, and he and his coworker continued their commute to the mall. Along the way, he casually wiped the doll dry and picked up a necklace lying beside her. The moment he touched it, the doll transformed into a real woman, but as soon as he set it down, she turned back into a doll. When he arrived at his workshop, stared at the doll's stunning features, secretly wishing she could become real. After checking to make sure no one was nearby, he couldn't resist leaning in for a quick kiss, and he went back to sorting the merchandise and absent mindedly removed the doll's necklace. Jesse, who had slept for a thousand years, suddenly awoke. She let out a sneeze, startling Jason so badly he tumbled onto the floor. Jesse, however, was thrilled because Jason looked exactly like her prince from a millennium ago. Just then, several workers from the delivery truck showed up. Jesse immediately froze, pretending to be a lifeless doll. After confirming the doll wasn't damaged, they left without suspicion. Jesse's stomach suddenly growled, so Jason drove her out to get food. She gazed at the world a thousand years later, amazed by everything around her. She even began eating enthusiastically.

Next, he set the internal temperature to 200 degrees. 30 minutes later, the door opened again. This procedure could reduce a normal adult to 1/200 of their size in an instant. To address Earth's overpopulation crisis, a doctor created this shrinking technology. It could compress an ordinary person to just 10 cm tall. This would drastically ease the pressure caused by overcrowding. Miniature residents produced in four years less trash than a full sized human generated in a single day. More importantly, in this tiny world, one thousand dollars held the value of 10 million. 1,000 square meter luxury villa cost only $99. As a poor man, he was naturally tempted by such an irresistible offer. So the next day he took his wife to visit the miniature paradise. They planned to undergo the shrinking procedure together. Before the process began, every bit of body hair had to be removed. Next, all their teeth had to be extracted. Teeth don't shrink. If left in, they would explode inside the skull. Luego escoltaron al pollito de regreso a la granja. voice_to_text: A blind mother went to pick up her daughter from school, but when the daughter saw her mother, she quickly covered the bell she was carrying, not wanting her mother to hear the sound. She didn't want her classmates to find out that her mother was blind. However, despite this, the mother still managed to recognize her by her scent. When they got home, the girl got into an argument with her mother. Just then, the mobile phone in her pocket rang. The mother, thinking her daughter was misbehaving, angrily threw the phone to the ground when she saw that it was broken. The daughter ran to her mother's room, destroyed the cassette tapes her mother treasured more than anything, and stormed out of the house. The parents waited until nightfall, but the daughter didn't come back. The next day, they heard on the recorder that the police had found a female body on the beach. They immediately went to the police station to identify it. The mother touched the body's arm and didn't find any scars, confirming that it wasn't her daughter. They went out on the streets searching from day until night, but they couldn't find her. However, at that moment, the girl was strolling with her boyfriend, unaware of how worried her parents were. When she finally came home, she discovered her parents weren't there. Seeing the broken cassette tapes on the floor, she realized what had happened.

But whenever I opened the door to check, there was nothing out there. And besides me and the old man in this house, there was no other living thing. So I suspected he was pretending to be blind and watching me whenever I fell asleep. But when the 53 degree liquor hit his eyes, he he did not react at all. Then I tried another test. While helping him walk, I deliberately guided him the wrong way. I even put a bright floral coat on him and played with a knife right in front of him. But none of it worked. He acted exactly like a real blind man, which meant he could not be spying on me. To clear my doubts once and for all, I went to the village priest for help. I was getting profiled. License and registration, he said. I quickly handed it all over. He took a look at my ID and laughed. 34? Yeah. Okay, kid, step out of the vehicle. He pushed me against the car and patted me down, asking again what school you go to. You're quite the reckless driver. Speeding, failure to signal, and your tail light looks cracked to me. My wife asked when she saw what I planned. It's not about the ticket, I told her. She didn't get it. But I'd seen too many kids get railroaded by officers like this one. voice_to_text: My wife bragged, I make the rules here, so I packed and let her rule her own loneliness. The control didn't happen overnight. First, comments about my clothes, then who I could spend time with, eventually how I should think. My friends disappeared one by one and bad influences. Family visits became rare with convenient excuses. I had become a guest in my own life. That week, she came home with shopping bags full of clothes she bought for me. Your wardrobe is embarrassing, she declared. These are more appropriate. I thanked her quietly while something inside me screamed. Later, she criticized how I loaded the dishwasher, reorganizing it completely. Just let me do it right, she snapped. And came comments about my weight, my ambition, how my family had no manners. Three days after that dinner party, I sat across from a lawyer in a coffee shop across town. Document everything, he advised. Keep records of controlling behavior, financial information, instances of emotional abuse. I created a secret email account at the library, opened a separate bank account, converting small amounts from paychecks, not enough to raise suspicion, but enough to build an emergency fund. I researched apartments in neighborhoods she'd never visit. The hardest part was maintaining normalcy. I continued nodding at her criticisms, playing the role I'd perfected. But I was now an actor, conscious of his performance rather than someone who'd forgotten he was on stage. Six weeks into preparations, she announced a weekend spa trip. You'll be fine on your own, I suppose. The night she criticized how I'd packed her suitcase, emptying it completely to refold everything while listing my deficiencies, any remaining doubt evaporated. After dropping her off, I drove straight to the bank, withdrew half our joint savings, legally mine, and deposited it into my new account. At home, I packed methodically, clothes, personal items, family photographs, only what was undeniably mine. I placed my house key and a sealed letter on the kitchen counter, brief stating I was leaving and would contact her through my lawyer. No explanations, no accusations, nothing that could be twisted. Driving away felt like emerging from underwater after nearly drowning. My phone stayed off until Sunday morning when I turned it on, 27 missed calls, 43 texts, 5 voicemails. I forwarded everything to my lawyer without reading them. Monday at work, she showed up in the lobby. We need to talk, she stated loud.

video_description: part1😭😭@TheJubalShowJubalinthemorningradioprogram“BrookeandJubal”#brookeandjubal#brookandjubalinthemorning#seconddate#seconddateupdate#prank
voice_to_text: You can live with us for exactly 90 days, my aunt said, sliding a printed schedule across the dinner table. I didn't know she was about to raise me better than my own parents ever did. I was 16 when child services called her. My mom had been arrested again, third time that year. My aunt Rachel didn't hesitate, but she had conditions. The schedule was brutal. Wake up 6:00am, eat breakfast, 30 minutes exercise, school, two hours homework before dinner, chores, rotation, lights out. Ten PM, no exceptions. This isn't a vacation, she said. You follow the rules or you leave. I arrived with one duffle bag and an attitude. My whole life had been chaos. Mom's boyfriends rotating through our apartment, eviction notices, dinner from gas stations. Structure felt like punishment. Week 1, I tested every boundary, stayed up past 10, left dishes in the sink. I finished my homework. Rachel didn't yell. She just pointed to the schedule taped on my bedroom door. Day seven, she said, 83 to go. She checked my homework like a drill sergeant, made me redo a whole essay because I didn't try. I told her she wasn't my real mom. She nodded and said, you're right. Real moms let you fail. I won't. Week two, I skipped the morning exercise, found her waiting at my bedroom door at 6:15 with running shoes. We can go together or you can go alone, but you're going. We ran two miles in silence. She Didn't lecture, just ran beside me. Week three, something shifted. She drove 40 minutes each way so I could stay at my old school. Never complained, never mentioned the gas money. She packed my lunch every morning with notes inside. You've got this, or proud of you, or bad days don't last. My friend Becca noticed your aunt makes your lunch. That's so weird. I shrugged, but I started keeping the notes. Week 5, I got a C on a history test. Hid it in my backpack. She found it doing laundry. We're fixing this, she said. Every night that week, she sat with me at the kitchen table, quizzed me on dates, Battle's treaties. She'd taught elementary school for 20 years before switching to nursing. She knew how to make things stick. I got a B on the next test. She put it on the fridge. Month two, I came home early, found her crying in the kitchen over bills.

I've been an ER nurse for nine years and had seen every kind of ink imaginable, but this one made my hands go numb. The guy on the gurney had come in with chest pains around two a m. Standard protocol stuff. I was taking his vitals when I lifted his left arm to check his pulse and saw it. A faded blue anchor with the letters RM under. My Uncle Ray had that exact tattoo. Same spot, same design. He'd gotten it in the Navy in 1987. Ray died in a car crash when I was 12. At least that's what my parents told me. The clipboard hit the floor. The patient opened his eyes. Okay, yeah, sorry. I bent down to grab it, but my vision was swimming. Just clumsy today. He grunted and closed his eyes again. I forced myself to keep working, wrapping the blood pressure cuff around his arm. But then I noticed his hands. The way his pinky finger curled slightly inward on the right hand. Ray had broken that finger in a bar fight, and it never healed straight. My dad used to joke about it at every family dinner. Sir, what's your name? My voice came out wrong. Marcus Webb. Not Ray Morrison? Of course not. Ray was dead. Closed casket funeral. My mom crying for weeks. But then he did this thing where he rubbed his left Eyebrow with his thumb when the doctor asked him a question. Ray did that exact movement when he was stressed. I watched him do it four more times during the examination. The doctor ordered an EKG. While setting up the leads, I had to pull his shirt up slightly. That's when I saw the second tattoo. A small compass rose on his ribs. Ray got that one the same day as the anchor. I knew because I'd seen the photos in my grandmother's album 100 times before she died. But there was something else. A newer tattoo just below it. Fresh, maybe 6 months old. It was a date. 0 8 15 2,019. My blood went cold. That was the day my cousin Bethany disappeared. Police said she ran away. She was 17. My aunt never recovered. She drank herself to death two years later. My hands were shaking so bad, I could barely attach the electrodes. You sure you're all right? The doctor asked me. Fine. Just tired. Marcus, if that was even his real name. Kept his eyes closed through the whole thing. But I couldn't stop staring at his face. The shape of his nose, the way his hairline receded at the temples. Even the small scar on his chin. From when Ray supposedly fell off a motorcycle at 19. The EKG came back normal. Probably just anxiety. The doctor said we'd keep him for observation. Anyway, I stepped out into the hallway and made myself walk. To the nurse's state. Pulled up his file. Insurance was under Marcus Webb, but the emergency contact made my stomach drop. The phone number listed was my grandmother's old landline, the one that got disconnected when she died eight years ago. I went back to his room. He was awake now, staring at the ceiling. Those tattoos, I said quietly. The anchor and compass. Military. He looked at me, and for just a second, something flickered across his face. Fear, maybe. Or recognition. Yeah. Long time ago. What branch? His jaw tightened. Navy. But I don't really talk about it. The way he said Navy, the exact inflection, the slight rest. It was Ray's voice. Pulled up a chair and sat down. Kept my voice steady. The date on your ribs. What's it mean? His whole body went rigid. None of your business. Bethany Morrison disappeared that day. He sat up fast, ripping off the EKG leads. Who the hell are you? Your niece, Claire. The color drained from his face.

She actually asked the consultant if they had anything similar to 1990 styles. The consultant looked confused. Carol pulled up photos of her dress on her phone, shoved them in everyone's face. I bought my dress anyway. Carol sulped the entire drive home. For six months, every wedding planning session became the Carol Show. She'd interrupt cake tasting to describe her seven tier cake. Two days later, the signed papers came back. Included was a handwritten note from my sister. I'm sorry. You'll be a better mother than I could ever be. No questions about her daughter, just another abdication packaged as a compliment. The house became mine. Olivia became mine. The life we built together, painful and unexpected as it began, was officially, legally ours. Years from now, when she asks about her mother, I'll tell her the truth gently, that some people aren't ready to be what their children need. voice_to_text: To help a ship dock faster, the mooring crew doesn't even wait for the vessel to come to a full stop before looping the mooring line around the bollard. But this is one of the biggest mooring mistakes you can make, because once that line tightens, it releases an incredible amount of force. If you don't let go at the exact right moment, your hand can get caught in an instant. And don't be fooled by how thick and strong those ropes look. They're trying to stop a ship that weighs tens of thousands of tons. If the rope snaps, it recoils like a whip with enough power to launch a 100 pound object into the air. In dummy tests, the line tore through metal railings and sliced a mannequin clean in half. Now imagine that happening to a real person. To avoid tragedies like this, mooring lines must be replaced regularly, no matter how good they look on the outside. Here's how it works. During docking, crew members throw a thin line with a heavy knot attached. One end of this thin line is tied to the main mooring rope and workers on shore pull the thin line in, dragging the heavy mooring line onto the dock. They secure it to the bollard while the rope is still loose, avoiding any sudden tension. That's how you keep a docking operation safe, smooth and free of disasters.

voice_to_text: How is liquid egg made? This is one of Japan's largest liquid egg factories, where millions of eggs are cracked every day. Any eggs that float to the surface are discarded, while the ones that pass the test are pushed onto a conveyor belt heading to the egg cracking machine. Here, the eggs are cracked automatically and quickly, and the shells are separated onto another conveyor, where they're collected and later used as organic fertilizer. voice_to_text: 3 a. M. In the watch tower, George jolts awake. Thank god it was just a nightmare. He glances back by chance and sees the woman across from him hasn't slept a wink either. Turns out they share the same mission, guarding this mysterious Canyon. Between them, multiple large jammers are installed on both sides of the Canyon. Making sure they work properly is George's daily job. After the handover with George, the previous guard leaves by plane. The truth is, no guard ever leaves this place alive. George in the watch tower doesn't know this yet. He just keeps working diligently every day. Apart from radio reports, he has no contact with the outside world. Even communication between the two towers is forbidden. One day, George hears a chainsaw from across the way. He can't resist looking through his electronic binoculars. That's when he discovers the guard opposite is a woman. Two months later, Anna's gunshot finally breaks the Canyon silence. It's her birthday today. Using cardboard signs, she asks George about his skills. George writes, pretty good shot. This instantly fires up Anna's competitive spirit. She nails a bottle with one shot, wants to show him what a real marksman looks like. But the next second, George fires off a round two. Just as they're both having fun, Anna suddenly senses danger at her feet. She slowly backs away, her first close encounter with a monster. No time to think. She quickly draws her pistol and fires. She Barely kills one when more monsters start climbing up. Lucky for her, George provides timely backup from the other side. With his dead eye accuracy, he doesn't miss a shot. One bullet, one kill. But when a falling monster triggers a mine, this sudden blast knocks Anna flat. Seeing her hurt, George immediately grabs the gatling gun and unleashes hell on the other side. Anna struggles to her feet and joins the fight, but there are just too many monsters. They keep coming no matter how many they kill. Fortunately, one monster trips the infrared alarm. The auto defense turrets activate on both sides. Instantly, seven or eight streams of fire sweep back and forth across the cliff face, finally wiping out every last monster. Seeing George worried about her, Anna crawls through the scattered shell casings and writes something on a cardboard sign. Next, they need to repair the damaged fences and replace the missing mines. While he's working, George notices Anna providing cover from the east side, can't help but feel touched. But right then, a drone suddenly appears from the Canyon. It hovers right in front of George like it's watching him. Luckily, the drone flies away before the auto turrets activate a false alarm for them both. After this battle, the Canyon returns to silence.
